<org.eclipse.epf.uma:ContentDescription xmi:version="2.0" xmlns:xmi="http://www.omg.org/XMI" xmlns:org.eclipse.epf.uma="http://www.eclipse.org/epf/uma/1.0.6/uma.ecore" xmlns:rmc="http://www.ibm.com/rmc" rmc:version="7.5.1" xmlns:epf="http://www.eclipse.org/epf" epf:version="1.5.1" xmi:id="-X3eaJbxQN4BEsMzWZeSN5Q" name="refining_user_stories_eclipse,_yaLh4NYBEd6NXbVE_51_NQ" guid="-X3eaJbxQN4BEsMzWZeSN5Q" changeDate="2010-11-02T10:02:41.896-0700" version="7.5.0">
  <mainDescription>&lt;h3>&#xD;
    Starting state&#xD;
&lt;/h3>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    This task is based on the assumption that you have already performed the &lt;a class=&quot;elementLinkWithUserText&quot;&#xD;
    href=&quot;./../../../practice.tech.user_story_driven_dev.extend-ibm/guidances/toolmentors/identifying_user_stories_5F08DB88.html&quot;&#xD;
     guid=&quot;_02o9QNYBEd6NXbVE_51_NQ&quot;>Identifying User Stories&lt;/a> task, which means that the backlog (or project plan) is&#xD;
    already populated with an initial set of epics and user stories ready to be prioritized and refined for the work on the&#xD;
    project iterations.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    All steps that follow&amp;nbsp;are performed in the Work Items perspective in the Eclipse-based interface of Rational Team&#xD;
    Concert. These instructions are based on the assumption that you are familiar with creating work items.&amp;nbsp;See &lt;a&#xD;
    href=&quot;http://pic.dhe.ibm.com/infocenter/clmhelp/v4r0/topic/com.ibm.team.workitem.doc/topics/t_creating_work_items.html&quot;&#xD;
    target=&quot;_blank&quot;>Creating work items&lt;/a>&amp;nbsp;and &lt;a&#xD;
    href=&quot;http://pic.dhe.ibm.com/infocenter/clmhelp/v4r0/topic/com.ibm.team.workitem.doc/topics/t_creating_work_items_web.html&quot;&#xD;
     target=&quot;_blank&quot;>Creating work items in the Web&lt;/a> interface for more information.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;h3>&#xD;
    Steps&#xD;
&lt;/h3>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    This task covers the following steps:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Prioritize user stories&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Break down user stories&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Consolidate common user stories&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&#xD;
&lt;h4>&#xD;
    Prioritize user stories&#xD;
&lt;/h4>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Prioritize user stories in the following way:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ol>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Find work items that are classified as the User Story type. See how to &lt;a&#xD;
        href=&quot;http://pic.dhe.ibm.com/infocenter/clmhelp/v4r0/topic/com.ibm.team.workitem.doc/topics/t_finding_work_items.html&quot;&#xD;
         target=&quot;_blank&quot;>Find work items&lt;/a>&amp;nbsp;in the Eclipse UI&amp;nbsp;or &lt;a&#xD;
        href=&quot;http://pic.dhe.ibm.com/infocenter/clmhelp/v4r0/topic/com.ibm.team.workitem.doc/topics/t_finding_work_items_web.html&quot;&#xD;
         target=&quot;_blank&quot;>Finding work items in the Web interface&lt;/a>.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Modify the priority of the desired user stories one-by-one or by &lt;a&#xD;
        href=&quot;http://pic.dhe.ibm.com/infocenter/clmhelp/v4r0/topic/com.ibm.team.workitem.doc/topics/t_modifying_multiple_work_items.html&quot;&#xD;
         target=&quot;_blank&quot;>modifying multiple user stories at once&lt;/a> &#xD;
        &lt;ol>&#xD;
            &lt;li>&#xD;
                Right-click the &lt;strong>P&lt;/strong> (Priority) cell of a user story.&#xD;
            &lt;/li>&#xD;
            &lt;li>&#xD;
                From the drop-down menu, select &lt;strong>Change Priority&lt;/strong>.&#xD;
            &lt;/li>&#xD;
            &lt;li>&#xD;
                Select the appropriate priority for the user story (Low, Medium, or High).&#xD;
            &lt;/li>&#xD;
        &lt;/ol>&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ol>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Alternatively, you can prioritize stories (one at the time) in the Eclipse UI in the following way:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ol>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;a&#xD;
        href=&quot;http://pic.dhe.ibm.com/infocenter/clmhelp/v4r0/topic/com.ibm.team.workitem.doc/topics/t_finding_work_items.html&quot;&#xD;
         target=&quot;_blank&quot;>Find work items&lt;/a> that are classified as the User Story type.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        In the list of user stories returned, double-click the desired user story to open the editor.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        In the editor window, click the &lt;strong>Priority&lt;/strong> drop-down menu to select the priority for the user story.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Select the appropriate priority for the user story (Low, Medium, or High).&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Click &lt;strong>Save&lt;/strong>.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ol>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    &lt;strong>Note:&lt;/strong>&lt;br />&#xD;
    Stories are first added to the backlog, which is identified in the &lt;strong>Filed Against&lt;/strong> field. When they are&#xD;
    ready for implementation, stories should be moved to a Sprint Backlog (Scrum Process template) or Iteration Plan (IBM&#xD;
    Practices for Agile Delivery Process template) in the &lt;strong>Planned For&lt;/strong> field.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;h4>&#xD;
    Break down user stories&#xD;
&lt;/h4>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Epics and other large user stories are broken down into right-sized user stories that can be assigned to team members&#xD;
    in one given iteration. Create as many fine-grained user stories as you need, as described in the &lt;a&#xD;
    class=&quot;elementLinkWithUserText&quot;&#xD;
    href=&quot;./../../../practice.tech.user_story_driven_dev.extend-ibm/guidances/toolmentors/identifying_user_stories_5F08DB88.html&quot;&#xD;
     guid=&quot;_02o9QNYBEd6NXbVE_51_NQ&quot;>Identifying User Stories&lt;/a> task. Then follow these steps to define the relationships&#xD;
    to show which epics originated which user stories:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ol>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Find an epic. For example, by running a standard or customized query that returns all work items of the Epic type.&#xD;
        (See &lt;a&#xD;
        href=&quot;http://pic.dhe.ibm.com/infocenter/clmhelp/v4r0/topic/com.ibm.team.workitem.doc/topics/t_finding_work_items.html&quot;&#xD;
         target=&quot;_blank&quot;>Finding work items&lt;/a> or &lt;a&#xD;
        href=&quot;http://pic.dhe.ibm.com/infocenter/clmhelp/v4r0/topic/com.ibm.team.workitem.doc/topics/t_finding_work_items_web.html&quot;&#xD;
         target=&quot;_blank&quot;>Finding work items in the Web interface&lt;/a>&amp;nbsp;for more information.)&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        In the list of epics returned by the query, click the epic that you want to edit to open the editor.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        In the epic editor, click the &lt;strong>Links&lt;/strong> tab&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        In the &lt;strong>Links&lt;/strong> section of the tab, click the &lt;strong>Add&lt;/strong> button and select&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Children&lt;/strong>.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Within the &lt;strong>Select Work Items&lt;/strong> window, type text to match the user story name or identifier.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        In the list of matching work items, select user stories that will be children of this epic.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Click &lt;strong>OK&lt;/strong>&amp;nbsp;and &lt;strong>Save&lt;/strong>.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ol>&#xD;
&lt;h4>&#xD;
    Consolidate common user stories&#xD;
&lt;/h4>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    As part of revising and refining user stories, consolidate&amp;nbsp;similar, common user stories to avoid duplication of&#xD;
    functionality in the system and a waste of time trying to solve similar problem. Mark duplicate user stories in the&#xD;
    following way:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ol>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Find potential duplicates (in the &lt;a&#xD;
        href=&quot;http://pic.dhe.ibm.com/infocenter/clmhelp/v4r0/topic/com.ibm.team.workitem.doc/topics/t_searching_for_duplicates.html&quot;&#xD;
         target=&quot;_blank&quot;>Eclipse UI&lt;/a>&amp;nbsp;or &lt;a&#xD;
        href=&quot;http://pic.dhe.ibm.com/infocenter/clmhelp/v4r0/topic/com.ibm.team.workitem.doc/topics/t_searching_for_duplicates_web.html&quot;&#xD;
         target=&quot;_blank&quot;>Web UI&lt;/a>) of a user story or run a query to find work items of the User Story type.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        In the list of stories returned, click the user story that you want to edit to open its editor.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        With the user story in &lt;strong>Identified&lt;/strong> or &lt;strong>In progress&lt;/strong> states, move the state to&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Defer&lt;/strong> and the reason to &lt;strong>Duplicate&lt;/strong>.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Click the &lt;strong>Links&lt;/strong> tab.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        In the &lt;strong>Links&lt;/strong> section of the tab, click the &lt;strong>Add&lt;/strong> button and select &lt;strong>Make&#xD;
        Duplicate of&lt;/strong>.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Within the &lt;strong>Select Work Items&lt;/strong> window, type text to match the user story name or identifier.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        In the list of matching work items, select the user story that this user story is a duplicate of.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Click &lt;strong>OK&lt;/strong> and &lt;strong>Save&lt;/strong>.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ol>&#xD;
&lt;h3>&#xD;
    Result&#xD;
&lt;/h3>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    The epics are broken down into finer-grained user stories and their parent-child relationship is defined. Prioritized&#xD;
    user stories are consolidated and at the right size to be assigned to an iteration. You can see results, for example,&#xD;
    in the Iteration Plan or in the Team Central and My Work views. See &lt;a&#xD;
    href=&quot;http://pic.dhe.ibm.com/infocenter/clmhelp/v4r0/topic/com.ibm.team.apt.doc/topics/t_view_work_items_ip.html&quot;&#xD;
    target=&quot;_blank&quot;>Viewing work items in a plan&lt;/a>,&amp;nbsp;&lt;a&#xD;
    href=&quot;http://pic.dhe.ibm.com/infocenter/clmhelp/v4r0/topic/com.ibm.team.workitem.doc/topics/c_work_item_perspective_view.html&quot;&#xD;
     target=&quot;_blank&quot;>Work items perspectives and views&lt;/a>, and &lt;a&#xD;
    href=&quot;http://pic.dhe.ibm.com/infocenter/clmhelp/v4r0/topic/com.ibm.jazz.dashboard.doc/topics/t_managing_dashboards.html&quot;&#xD;
     target=&quot;_blank&quot;>Managing dashboards in the Web interface&lt;/a>&amp;nbsp;for more information.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
